definition.value: The conjugate base of vitexin 2''-O-alpha-L-rhamnoside arising from deprotonation of the OH group at position 7 on the chromene.
The conjugate base of 3'-O-methyltricetin arising from selective deprotonation of the 7-OH position; major species at pH 7.3.
Tetraanion of 2,3-dehydroacyl-CoA arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups.
The conjugate base of 3',5'-di-O-methyltricetin arising from selective deprotonation of the 7-OH position; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of 3',4',5'-O-trimethyltricetin arising from selective deprotonation of the 7-OH position; major species at pH 7.3.
A pentaanionic form of coenzyme A-glutathione mixed disulfide; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of (5Z,7E,9E,14Z,17Z)-icosapentaenoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A polymer is a mixture, which is composed of macromolecules of different kinds and which may be differentiated by composition, length, degree of branching etc..
A homopolymer is a polymer composed of macromolecules, all of which are derived from one species of monomer.
Poly(vinyl alcohol) polymer is a homopolymer, which is composed of poly(vinyl alcohol) macromolecules.
A poly(alkylene) polymer is a homopolymer, composed of poly(alkylene) macromolecules.
The ion of overall charge -3 formed from undecaprenyldiphospho-N-acetylmuramoyl-L-alanyl-D-gamma-glutamyl-L-lysyl-D-alanyl-D-alanine at pH 7.3.
The organophosphate oxoanion of overall charge -3 formed from lipid II [undecaprenyldiphospho-N-acetyl-(N-acetylglucosaminyl)muramoyl-L-alanyl-D-gamma-glutamyl-L-lysyl-D-alanyl-D-alanine] at pH 7.3.
Polyethylene polymer is a poly(alkylene) polymer composed of polyethylene macromolecules.
Poly(N,N'-methylenebisacrylamide) polymer is  a homopolymer, composed of poly(N,N'-methylenebisacrylamide) macromolecules.
The conjugate base of (+)-epitaxifolin arising from selective deprotonation of the 7-OH group; major species at pH 7.3.
Any anion arising from deprotonation of at least one OH group in a flavonoid compound.
The zwitterion formed from L-proline by proton transfer from the carboxy group to the ring nitrogen. It is the predominant species at physiological pH.

A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of alpha-N-acetylneuraminyl-(2->6)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function of the alpha-N-acetylneuraminyl residue.
The zwitterion formed from cis-3-hydroxy-L-proline by proton transfer from the carboxy group to the ring nitrogen. It is the predominant species at physiological pH.
The conjugate base of a 5'-acylphosphoadenosine; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of tricetin arising from selective deprotonation of the 7-OH position; major species at pH 7.3.
The dianion resulting from the removal of two protons from the diphosphate group of N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl-1-diphospho-ditrans,polycis-undecaprenol.
The conjugate base of pelargonidin 3-O-rutinoside; major species at pH 7.3.
A cyclic tetrapyrrole anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of cobalt-sirohydrochlorin; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of estrone 3-sulfate; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of N-formyl-D-kynurenine having an anionic carboxy group and a protonated amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A cyclic tetrapyrrole anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of siroheme; major species at pH 7.3.

A cyclic hexapeptide echinocandin antibiotic which exerts its effect by inhibiting the synthesis of 1,3-beta-D-glucan, an integral component of the fungal cell wall. It is used as the sodium salt for the treatment of invasive candidiasis, and of aspergillosis in patients who are intolerant of other therapy.
A precorrin carboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of cobalt-precorrin-2; major species at pH 7.3.
The amide obtained by formal condensation of linoleic acid with cyclohexylamine.
Anionic form of dermatan 6'-sulfate arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid and sulfate groups of the repeating units; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of cocaine arising from protonation of the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
The dianion resulting from the removal of two protons from the diphosphate group of N-acetyl-beta-D-mannosaminyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl undecaprenyl diphosphate.
Conjugate base of S-acylglutathionate having anionic carboxy groups and a protonated amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion obtained from dermatan by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid groups of the repeating units; the major species at pH 7.3.
A pentahydroxyflavone that is flavone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 5, 7, 2', 4' and 5'.
A precorrin carboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of cobalt-precorrin-3; major species at pH 7.3.
A precorrin carboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of  cobalt-precorrin-4; major species at pH 7.3.
A precorrin carboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of cobalt-precorrin-5A; major species at pH 7.3.
A precorrin carboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of cobalt-precorrin-5B; major species at pH 7.3.
A precorrin carboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of cobalt-precorrin-6A; major species at pH 7.3.

A carbohydrate acid derivative anion that is the conjugate base of alpha-N-acetylneuraminosyl-(2->3)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosylceramide arising from deprotonation of the neuraminosyl carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An isocyanate having a 2-methoxy-4-nitrophenyl group attached to the nitrogen.
An isocyanate having a 2-phenylethyl group attached to the nitrogen.
Conjugate base of the alpha-N-acetylneuraminyl-2,3-beta-D-galactosyl-1,3-N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminyl group arising from deprotonation of the neuraminosyl carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
